{
  "doc_id": "51376",
  "text": "Although the spatial coverage of our sensor is smaller than that of MRI (MRI: whole brain (220 × 220 mm = 4.84 × 10 4 mm 2 ), our sensor: 0.72 mm × 3.0 mm = 2.16 mm 2 ) 6 , our sensor is advantageous for the spatial and temporal resolution (MRI:~4.0 mm, 0.17 frames s −1 , our sensor: 23.55 μm, 50 frames s −1 ) 6 . Also, the spatial coverage of our sensor is larger than regular two-photon microscopy (2PMS), an imaging technique for deep brain recording, or single-photon imaging through a GRIN lens (our sensor: 2.16 mm 2 , 2PMS:~0.25 mm 2 , GRIN lens:~0.785 mm 2 with more invasion) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Our sensor is also superior to the other imaging techniques in terms of temporal resolution (our sensor: 50 frames s −1 , 2PMS: 30 frames s −1 , MRI:~0.17 frames s −1 , 31 P spectrometry: several minutes per frame) [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Based on the advanced temporal resolution, we successfully demonstrated the detection of the sub-second order dynamics of the change in brain pH triggered by visual stimulation (Supplementary Fig. 4 ).",
